data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new implicit span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` in an expression tree to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent calls to span-based methods**, so this throws at runtime (typically `NotSupportedException` from the expression tree interpreter).

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` so the compiler picks the LINQ overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in an expression tree. The same fix applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays, which now binds to the in-place `Span` version instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`.
